(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories London - Britain plans to give afterschool cyber security training to thousands of teenagers in a bid to protect the country from online attacks.The government says it has earmarked &pound;20m for a Cyber Schools Program, due to start in September.The department for culture, media and sport said on Saturday it hoped almost 6 000 students aged 14 to 18 will complete the extra-curricular course by 2021 and that many would go on to cyber security careers.Culture Minister Matt Hancock said the "these extracurricular clubs will help identify and inspire future talent."Parliament's Public Accounts Committee said last week that Britain's electronic spy agency, GCHQ, dealt with 200 cyberattacks a month in 2015, double the number in 2014.The committee said skills shortages are undermining Britain's ability to block cyber attacks.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.